Thank you to all who were patient and flexible with arrival and dismissal today, 9/8/2020.
Some adjustments for Wednesday Sept. 9.
Arrival - Drop off can start at 7:50 but students will not enter building until 7:55. Please wait until staff are out back to assist with safety.
Dismissal - Please have a piece of paper with last name of student/students and youngest grade level to show staff at traffic cones.
We hope that these adjustments will assist in making the processes smoother and faster.

Registration day, today Thursday, August 20, 9 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. If you need to drop off paperwork or to use computers stop by. Staff will be in the lobby to assist you. Physical distancing and masks are required. Thank you for your understanding and patience.

Looking forward to a great year in-person or on-line.

shared_text:
Newberry Athletics
August 7 at 5:24 PM 路

After 3 AD meetings that ended with more questions than they started with here is our plan.

AS OF NOW: Fall Sports will start as scheduled.
Monday August 10 Football will have its first practice. There will be no pads (Helmets only) for the first week.
Wednesday August 12 both Volleyball and Cross Country will start.

Some items to note. If you had a physical last year you will not have to get one this year, but will have to fill out a health questionnaire.

Locker Rooms WILL NOT be in use. Come to practice ready to practice.

Masks must be worn to and from practice.

Coaches will have other instructions for you.

Welcome back, stay safe and GO INDIANS

Tahquamenon Area Library
June 15 at 5:13 PM 路

Great News! Tahquamenon Area Library staff got the book drop up and running today. You can now start to return those items you've had since March.

Don't worry about rushing out though. You will not be charged fines on the those items until late August.

Please note that items returned in the book drop will not immediately be removed from your account. Due to required item quarantine procedures there will be a lag in when the books are returned and when they are checked in. You will not receive fines because of this.

If the book drop is full, please try to return those items at a later date. You will not be penalized. There are a lot of people with outstanding items and the book drop might reach capacity if everyone returns items at once. Forcing books into a full bin will result into damage to those items.

This is different than the P-EBT cards that were sent recently. Below will be based off of eligible students. Any questions need to be sent to the email below.

The Summer EBT for Children (SEBTC) program will be providing free, healthy groceries to students eligible for free and reduced-price school meals this summer. Eligible students in our district will receive an SEBTC card pre-loaded with $30 worth of nutritious foods per summer month (June, July and August). Healthy foods such as milk, eggs, fresh fruits and vegetables are included in the food package. Families can use the SEBTC card in any WIC authorized store across Michigan.
SEBTC is a program of the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services, Women, Infants and Children (WIC) program, in collaboration with Michigan Department of Education. SEBTC has been funded by the USDA. For more information about which districts have been chosen or the program, visit www.sebtc-mi.com.

May 6 at 3:33 PM 路

Working Wednesday: Choices are a powerful parenting tool. Offer your child two choices you are okay with, such as carrots or peas for dinner? Or do you want to do your homework now or later? If your child won't choose, you choose for them. Choices should be given before a child resists and shouldn't be used as a punishment in disguise. Choices reduce resistance, share power, provide boundaries, strengthen relationships and increase decision making. #extensionextras #workingwednesday https://www.canr.msu.edu/resources/the-power-of-choices-for-children

April 1 at 9:37 PM 路

We can still be together, even while we are apart. The CAMP has been offering teletherapy to our students from the time all Michigan schools were closed to keep us healthy.

Joining in on a teletherapy session is quick and easy...and we can walk you through the steps. It requires no downloads or software and you can access it in the time it takes to type in your name! Make an appointment by calling our office at 293-3226 ext 1427, and we'll give you the link to join! Teletherapy is private/confidential and is HIPAA compliant. As always, let us know if you have any questions!

Dear Tahquamenon Area School Community,

Governor Whitmer in your press conference this morning, Monday, March 23, announced "Stay Home, Stay Safe" executive order until April 13. She announced then that schools will be closed until April 13 also. This is a week longer than first reported.

The distribution of meals done by the school WILL still take place as this is viewed as an essential service.

Please be safe out there. The school is working hard to navigate through this situation as best we can. I'll keep you updated.

Stacy Price

MHSAA
March 11 at 6:44 PM 路

 COVID-19 UPDATE 
The Michigan High School Athletic Association is planning to conduct all remaining winter postseason tournaments as scheduled. However, based on the recommendations from Gov. Gretchen Whitmer this afternoon, the MHSAA is finalizing plans that will either prohibit or allow limited spectators through this Saturdays events.

This weekends Boys Swimming & Diving Finals will be held as scheduled at Oakland University and the Holland Aquatic Center, but will be conducted with no on-site spectators. All events at both Swim Final locations will be streamed live at MHSAA.tv.

Specific plans and policies for spectators at this weekends Ice Hockey Semifinals & Finals, Girls Gymnastic Finals, Girls Regional Basketball and Boys District Basketball games will be provided by 10 a.m. Thursday, March 12. Spectator plans for the final two weeks of the Girls and Boys Basketball Tournaments will be provided by Monday, March 16.

Updates will be posted as necessary to the MHSAA Website at https://www.mhsaa.com/coronavirus.

post_text:
D.E.A.R. is Drop Everything And Read. Beginning Monday, January 27, students and staff will be reading for 20 minutes with their second hour teachers before class begins. This change is providing time for students to stop and read.

This decision was made by staff (7-12) after they looked into our student NWEA data in all content areas. They recognized the need for our students to improve their vocabulary and their ability to read academically. They also found it important to provide students with time to find or rekindle their love of reading. They are hoping to see improvements across the board

Off to a great start!!!

Thank you Mrs. Browning for starting this club this year.

post_text: Local TAS eigth grade student, Liam Rao, recently competed as a member of Team USA, competing in creative weapons at The World Karate Championship, representing Black Dragon Martial Arts based in Sault Ste Marie. Liam qualified at a regional event last February in Ohio, he then went to Nationals in June in Detroit where the top 4 in each event went on to team USA. Many countries were represented including USA, Canada, Mexico, Venezuela, Argentina, Ireland, and Britain. He has been in Taekwondo since age 7 and this is his first time at The World Championships. Congratulations Liam on your extraordinary accomplishments, what an honor!! Below is a video of his routine.
